Stem: In the Piney Woods ecosystem with tall pine trees, few other tall trees, small shrubs and grasses — which bird from the table is most likely to live there?
Image/Diagram Description: Table: Four Texas Bird Species with habitat/food characteristics — Burrowing owl (underground nests, open areas), Roseate spoonbill (nests above water, eats fish), Red-cockaded woodpecker (nests in old trees, eats sap/insects from bark), Golden-cheeked warbler (nests in oaks/junipers in canyons).
Choices: A) Burrowing owl, B) Roseate spoonbill, C) Red-cockaded woodpecker, D) Golden-cheeked warbler
Scenario Justification: Rich ecosystem description with specific data table about bird characteristics. Students must match habitat needs to ecosystem features using evidence.
SEP Justification: Engages 'Analyzing and Interpreting Data' — students must read the data table and evaluate which bird's requirements match the Piney Woods description. Multi-step reasoning.
DCI Justification: Requires applying understanding of organism-environment relationships using specific trait data. Goes beyond recall to evidence-based matching.
CCC Justification: Engages Structure and Function (nest in trees + eats bark insects → needs forest) and Patterns (matching habitat features to organism needs).
Key Recommendation: Excellent data-driven question. Students analyze a real ecosystem and match organisms to it using evidence from a data table.

Stem: Diagrams of four different insect life cycles shown. Which insect goes through complete metamorphosis?
Image/Diagram Description: Four life cycle diagrams showing different insect developmental stages — one shows egg→larva→pupa→adult (complete metamorphosis), others show incomplete metamorphosis or simple growth.
Choices: A-D (four diagrams)
Scenario Justification: Provides visual life cycle diagrams but the task is identifying complete metamorphosis — applying a known concept to visual data.
SEP Justification: Engages 'Analyzing and Interpreting Data' — students interpret life cycle diagrams. However, it's recognition/classification rather than deep analysis.
DCI Justification: Tests understanding of complete vs. incomplete metamorphosis. Application level.
CCC Justification: Engages Patterns (recognize the complete metamorphosis pattern across stages).
Key Recommendation: Better than text-only life cycle recall because it uses diagrams. Could improve by showing an unfamiliar organism's stages and asking students to explain whether it shows complete metamorphosis.

Stem: Toy truck experiment: Rachel pushes right, Kobe pushes left. Table shows 5 trials with different forces. Which statement explains what caused the truck to move in Trials 3 and 4 but stay still in Trials 1, 2, and 5?
Image/Diagram Description: Diagram of hands pushing toy truck from both sides + data table showing 5 trials with force amounts for Rachel (right) and Kobe (left) and resulting truck movement.
Choices: A) When one student pushed with more force the truck rolled, B) When both pushed with same force the truck rolled, C) When one pushed with more force the truck stayed still, D) When one stopped before the other the truck stayed still
Scenario Justification: Rich experimental scenario with real data table showing 5 trials. Students must analyze the data pattern to identify what causes movement vs. stillness. Genuine scientific investigation context.
SEP Justification: Directly engages 'Analyzing and Interpreting Data' — students must examine 5 data points, identify the pattern linking force differences to movement, and select the correct explanation. Strong practice engagement.
DCI Justification: Requires applying understanding of balanced vs. unbalanced forces using actual experimental data. Deep DCI engagement.
CCC Justification: Engages Cause and Effect (unbalanced forces cause movement) and Patterns (identifying the pattern across 5 trials that predicts when the truck moves).
Key Recommendation: One of the strongest G3 questions. Real experimental data, multi-trial analysis, genuine pattern identification. Approaches Doing Science level.

Stem: Which statement best explains the answer to the previous question? (Follow-up to Q3 about toy truck experiment)
Image/Diagram Description: None
Choices: A) An object at rest still has forces acting upon it, B) An object with balanced forces has zero net movement, C) Forces that are unbalanced cause movement, D) Objects in contact exert forces upon each other
Scenario Justification: Part B of the toy truck investigation. Students must connect the data pattern to a general principle about forces. Multi-part item design.
SEP Justification: Engages 'Constructing Explanations' — students must identify the underlying principle that explains the pattern they identified in Q3. Builds on prior analysis.
DCI Justification: Requires understanding and articulating the principle of balanced vs. unbalanced forces. Conceptual depth.
CCC Justification: Directly engages Cause and Effect — unbalanced forces cause movement. Students must explicitly state this causal relationship.
Key Recommendation: Excellent Part B that requires students to connect data to principle. Multi-part design mirrors MAP format.

Stem: A bright-red male cardinal comes to a school bird feeder every morning, makes chirping sounds. Which is a learned behavior?
Image/Diagram Description: None
Choices: A) Having red feathers, B) Eating seeds during the day, C) Coming to the bird feeder each morning, D) Making a chirping sound
Scenario Justification: Basic scenario about a cardinal. Task is identifying learned vs. inherited behavior — largely recall.
SEP Justification: No meaningful practice engagement. Classification/recall task.
DCI Justification: Tests inherited vs. learned behavior distinction. Grade-appropriate but basic.
CCC Justification: No CCC engagement.
Key Recommendation: Standard inherited/learned recall question. Same as G3.12 Q4.

Stem: Table lists characteristics of four animals (Muskrat, Mallard, Mink, Western grebe). What features do their ecosystems most likely have in common?
Image/Diagram Description: Table showing four animals with characteristics suggesting aquatic habitats — webbed/partially webbed feet, eats fish, dives and spears fish.
Choices: A) Dry rocky mountains, B) Forests of pine trees, C) Tall spiny cacti, D) Lakes and rivers
Scenario Justification: Provides a data table of animal characteristics. Students must analyze shared traits to determine the common ecosystem feature. Data-driven.
SEP Justification: Engages 'Analyzing and Interpreting Data' — students must identify the pattern across four organisms' traits that points to a shared habitat type.
DCI Justification: Requires applying understanding of organism-environment relationships using trait evidence.
CCC Justification: Engages Structure and Function (webbed feet, aquatic hunting → water habitats) and Patterns (common trait → common habitat).
Key Recommendation: Good data-driven question. Students analyze a table to find common habitat features.

Stem: Meerkats confront predator snakes by working together — hissing, biting, surrounding. Why do they do this?
Image/Diagram Description: None
Choices: A) Group behavior as survival strategy to deter the snake, B) Practice fighting skills, C) Naturally curious, D) Playful activity for social bonds
Scenario Justification: Presents a specific, fascinating phenomenon (meerkat group defense). Students must explain the adaptive advantage of the behavior.
SEP Justification: Engages 'Constructing Explanations' — connecting observed behavior to survival advantage. However, the correct answer is fairly obvious.
DCI Justification: Requires understanding of how group behaviors function as survival strategies. Goes beyond simple recall.
CCC Justification: Engages Cause and Effect (group confrontation causes predator deterrence → survival) and Structure and Function (group behavior serves protection function).
Key Recommendation: Good phenomenon with engaging context. Answer is somewhat obvious. Could add competing explanations that require evidence evaluation.

Stem: Duckweed is free-floating with a single root. Which ecosystem type?
Image/Diagram Description: Illustration of duckweed plant.
Choices: A) Wetland with slow-moving water, B) Coastal with rough waves, C) Desert, D) Underground river
Scenario Justification: Same as G3.12 Q1. Organism-habitat matching with some trait reasoning.
SEP Justification: Limited reasoning — connecting organism traits to suitable habitat.
DCI Justification: Basic organism-environment relationship. Recall-level.
CCC Justification: Implicitly engages Structure and Function.
Key Recommendation: Repeated across multiple tests. Basic habitat matching.

Stem: Which table correctly classifies statements about weather and climate?
Image/Diagram Description: Four tables classifying weather/climate statements differently.
Choices: A-D (four classification tables)
Scenario Justification: Same concept as G3.12 Q7. Classification task with table format.
SEP Justification: Basic classification — sorting statements by definition.
DCI Justification: Tests weather vs. climate distinction at classification level.
CCC Justification: Implicitly engages Patterns (time-scale patterns).
Key Recommendation: Classification recall in table format.

Stem: Student raises a parrot — which behavior was learned from living in the student's home?
Image/Diagram Description: None
Choices: A) Flaps wings on perch, B) Loud scream, C) Imitates family dog barking, D) Tucks head under wing
Scenario Justification: Same question as G3.12 Q4. No phenomenon. Pure recall.
SEP Justification: No practice engagement. Classification recall.
DCI Justification: Tests inherited vs. learned at recall level.
CCC Justification: No CCC.
Key Recommendation: Exact duplicate of G3.12 Q4.

Stem: Fill blank: _____ is what happens when a seed begins to grow into a new plant.
Image/Diagram Description: None
Choices: A) Germination, B) Pollination, C) Reproduction, D) Fertilization
Scenario Justification: No phenomenon. Pure vocabulary recall.
SEP Justification: No practice engagement. Definition recall.
DCI Justification: Tests a vocabulary term, not understanding.
CCC Justification: No CCC.
Key Recommendation: Pure vocabulary question. No place on an NGSS-aligned assessment.

Stem: Tomato plant characteristics listed. Which is least likely to be inherited?
Image/Diagram Description: None
Choices: A) Flower color, B) Leaf shape, C) Type of roots, D) Number of tomatoes
Scenario Justification: Same as G3.12 Q16. Some reasoning about inherited vs. environmentally influenced traits.
SEP Justification: Basic 'Constructing Explanations' — distinguishing inherited from variable traits.
DCI Justification: Requires understanding that some traits vary with environment. Goes beyond simple recall.
CCC Justification: Engages Cause and Effect (environment affects fruit number).
Key Recommendation: Good reasoning question. Exact duplicate of G3.12 Q16.

Stem: Ring magnets on pencil — both S poles facing. What happens when they get close?
Image/Diagram Description: Image of ring magnets on a pencil.
Choices: A) Attract, B) Repel, C) No interaction, D) Break
Scenario Justification: Simple magnet scenario. Task is applying like-poles-repel rule — largely recall.
SEP Justification: No meaningful practice. Applying a memorized rule.
DCI Justification: Tests magnet pole interaction. Basic recall-application.
CCC Justification: No CCC engagement required.
Key Recommendation: Basic magnet rule recall.

Stem: Tundra characteristics described. Which pair of animals is LEAST likely to live there?
Image/Diagram Description: Four pairs of animal images — including tropical species.
Choices: A-D (animal pair images)
Scenario Justification: Same as G3.12 Q10. Habitat data provided, students evaluate animal suitability.
SEP Justification: Basic reasoning — connecting habitat data to organism survival.
DCI Justification: Applies organism-environment relationship understanding.
CCC Justification: Engages Structure and Function implicitly.
Key Recommendation: Same as G3.12 Q10.

Stem: Which characteristics of a friend are learned behaviors? Select TWO.
Image/Diagram Description: None
Choices: A) Brown eyes, B) Draws well, C) Has freckles, D) Reads daily, E) Blonde hair
Scenario Justification: Same as G3.12 Q20. No phenomenon. Classification recall.
SEP Justification: No practice engagement.
DCI Justification: Tests inherited vs. learned at basic level.
CCC Justification: No CCC.
Key Recommendation: Exact duplicate of G3.12 Q20.

Stem: Postcard from Cairo shows sunny sky and warm clear day. What does this describe?
Image/Diagram Description: None
Choices: A) Weather, B) Climate, C) Neither, D) Temperature
Scenario Justification: Simple scenario. Students must recognize that a specific day's conditions are weather, not climate.
SEP Justification: No meaningful practice. Applying a definition to a scenario.
DCI Justification: Tests weather vs. climate distinction at the simplest level.
CCC Justification: No CCC engagement.
Key Recommendation: Simple definition application.

Stem: Builder compares roof designs for high-wind area. Trapped wind creates forces. Which design best protects?
Image/Diagram Description: Image showing three different roof designs with wind flow patterns.
Choices: A) All equal, B) Roof 3 best — stays on in strong winds, C) Roof 1 — wind blows past walls, D) Roof 2 — no wind trapped
Scenario Justification: Engineering design problem with specific constraint (high winds). Students must evaluate three designs using principles of wind force.
SEP Justification: Engages 'Engaging in Argument from Evidence' — students evaluate engineering designs against a specific criterion (wind protection). Must reason about force/wind interactions.
DCI Justification: Requires applying understanding of forces to engineering design evaluation.
CCC Justification: Engages Cause and Effect (wind shape interaction → force on roof) and Structure and Function (roof shape → wind resistance).
Key Recommendation: Good engineering design question with visual data.

Stem: Salvia plant investigation — 4 plants at 25°C, exposed to different temps every 3 days. Figure shows results. In which ways were the salvia plants affected by temperature?
Image/Diagram Description: Four salvia plant illustrations showing plants exposed to different temperatures — varying heights but similar shapes/flowers.
Choices: A) Height of plant, B) Shape of leaves, C) Shape of flowers, D) Number of flowers
Scenario Justification: Rich investigation scenario with controlled experiment. Students must analyze visual data (plant diagrams) to determine which variable changed.
SEP Justification: Engages 'Analyzing and Interpreting Data' — students examine experimental results (plant diagrams) to determine how temperature affected the plants.
DCI Justification: Requires understanding of how environmental factors affect plant growth. Application to experimental data.
CCC Justification: Engages Cause and Effect (temperature → plant height change).
Key Recommendation: Good investigation data analysis. Part of a multi-question item set.

Stem: Part A: In which month would salvia plants most likely grow best? (Using temperature data from Leesville, Louisiana graph)
Image/Diagram Description: Bar graph showing monthly high temperatures in Leesville, Louisiana.
Choices: A) April, B) June, C) August, D) September
Scenario Justification: Part A of multi-part item. Students must connect experimental findings (best growth at 25°C) with climate data (which month is closest to 25°C).
SEP Justification: Engages 'Analyzing and Interpreting Data' — cross-referencing experimental results with climate data to make a prediction.
DCI Justification: Requires synthesizing investigation findings with real-world data. Multi-step reasoning.
CCC Justification: Engages Cause and Effect (temperature → growth) and Patterns (matching optimal temperature to seasonal data).
Key Recommendation: Excellent multi-part question requiring cross-referencing two data sources.

Stem: Part B: Which evidence best supports the answer to Part A?
Image/Diagram Description: None
Choices: A) Below 20°C, B) Close to 25°C, C) Close to 30°C, D) Above 30°C
Scenario Justification: Part B requiring students to cite evidence for their answer. Must connect the experimental control temperature (25°C) to the prediction.
SEP Justification: Engages 'Engaging in Argument from Evidence' — students must identify which evidence supports their claim. Explicit evidence citation.
DCI Justification: Requires understanding that optimal growth occurred at 25°C and using this as evidence.
CCC Justification: Engages Cause and Effect — temperature causes different growth rates.
Key Recommendation: Excellent Part B. Multi-part design with evidence citation mirrors MAP format perfectly.

Stem: Magnets hung at different heights above tacks. Different numbers of tacks attracted. What can students conclude?
Image/Diagram Description: Diagram showing 4 magnets at different heights picking up different numbers of tacks.
Choices: A) Magnet 1 and 3 strongest — closest to tacks, B) Magnet 2 and 3 strongest — reach more middle tacks, C) Magnet 3 and 4 strongest — pick up greatest number, D) Magnet 2 and 4 strongest — pick up tacks from greater distance
Scenario Justification: Investigation scenario with visual data. Students must analyze which magnets are strongest based on the evidence (picking up tacks from farther away).
SEP Justification: Engages 'Analyzing and Interpreting Data' and 'Constructing Explanations' — students must interpret the diagram data and identify which evidence demonstrates the strongest magnets.
DCI Justification: Requires understanding of magnetic force and distance relationship. Applied through experimental evidence.
CCC Justification: Engages Cause and Effect (magnet strength → ability to attract from distance) and Patterns (identifying which magnets perform best).
Key Recommendation: Strong experimental data analysis question.

Stem: Horse family diagram — mother (gray), father (black and white spotted), foal (gray and white spotted). Which traits did the foal inherit?
Image/Diagram Description: Diagram showing horse mother (solid gray), father (black and white patches), and foal (gray with white patches, white face).
Choices: A) White tail from mother, B) Solid body from mother, C) Spotted body from father, D) White face from both parents
Scenario Justification: Visual data showing parent and offspring traits. Students must analyze visual evidence to determine which traits were inherited from which parent.
SEP Justification: Engages 'Analyzing and Interpreting Data' — students examine visual evidence of trait inheritance across generations.
DCI Justification: Requires applying understanding of inheritance by comparing specific visual traits across parent-offspring.
CCC Justification: Engages Patterns (offspring traits match parent traits in predictable ways) and Cause and Effect (inheritance causes trait similarity).
Key Recommendation: Good visual evidence question about inheritance.

Stem: Child throws toy airplane. Which type of force?
Image/Diagram Description: None
Choices: A) Push, B) Pull, C) Wind, D) Tension
Scenario Justification: No phenomenon. Pure recall of force types. Trivially simple.
SEP Justification: No practice engagement.
DCI Justification: Tests basic force concept at definitional level.
CCC Justification: No CCC.
Key Recommendation: Trivially simple. No place on an assessment.

Stem: Fish swim together during migration. Why? Pick most likely reason.
Image/Diagram Description: Image of a large school of fish swimming together.
Choices: A) Follow a leader fish, B) Make a pretty pattern, C) Buddy system — safety from predators, D) Ocean current pushes them
Scenario Justification: Presents a real phenomenon (fish migration in schools). Students must identify the survival advantage of group behavior.
SEP Justification: Engages 'Constructing Explanations' at a basic level. The correct answer is somewhat obvious.
DCI Justification: Tests understanding of group behavior and survival. Basic application.
CCC Justification: Engages Cause and Effect (group swimming → predator protection).
Key Recommendation: Has a nice phenomenon but the answer is obvious.

Stem: Which is most likely to become a fossil?
Image/Diagram Description: None
Choices: A) Tree leaf eaten by animal, B) Fish consumed by scavengers, C) Dinosaur bone buried deep in sediment, D) Fern killed in fire
Scenario Justification: Basic scenario. Students must apply understanding of fossil formation conditions.
SEP Justification: Basic 'Constructing Explanations' — connecting fossilization requirements to scenarios.
DCI Justification: Tests understanding of conditions needed for fossilization.
CCC Justification: Engages Cause and Effect (burial in sediment → preservation).
Key Recommendation: Basic application of fossilization concept.

Stem: Which is NOT a trait of an organism?
Image/Diagram Description: None
Choices: A) The way it looks, B) Amount of oxygen in environment, C) The way it behaves, D) Color of fur/feathers
Scenario Justification: No phenomenon. Pure definitional question about what constitutes a 'trait.'
SEP Justification: No practice engagement. Vocabulary/definition recall.
DCI Justification: Tests definition of 'trait' at the most basic level.
CCC Justification: No CCC.
Key Recommendation: Pure definition recall.

Stem: What temperature is shown by this thermometer?
Image/Diagram Description: Image of a thermometer showing a specific temperature.
Choices: Tech-enhanced item
Scenario Justification: No phenomenon. Reading a measurement instrument. Basic skill.
SEP Justification: Engages a basic measurement skill but no science practice at a meaningful level.
DCI Justification: Tests instrument reading, not science understanding.
CCC Justification: No CCC.
Key Recommendation: Measurement skill, not science reasoning.

Stem: Town filled in swamp, fewer frogs. Students tested 3 solutions in 3 ponds. Data table shows results. Which claim is best supported?
Image/Diagram Description: Data table: Pond A (floating boards) = 5 egg masses; Pond B (water plants) = 14; Pond C (plastic frog) = 3. Started with 4 each.
Choices: A) Plastic frog best because looks real, B) None help because all changed, C) Water plants best because gave protected places for eggs, D) Shade boards best because fewer materials
Scenario Justification: Excellent engineering/investigation scenario. Students lost habitat, tested solutions, collected data. Students must evaluate claims against experimental data. Rich context.
SEP Justification: Directly engages 'Engaging in Argument from Evidence' — students evaluate four competing claims against a data table. Must identify which claim is supported by the evidence and which reasoning is valid.
DCI Justification: Requires applying understanding of organism needs (frogs need protected areas) to evaluate engineering solutions.
CCC Justification: Engages Cause and Effect (habitat features → frog reproduction success) and Systems (ecosystem disruption → solution design → data collection).
Key Recommendation: Outstanding question. Real engineering problem, real data, claim evaluation. One of the best G3 questions across all tests.

Stem: Papers blow off desks when fan is on. Ms. Chen gives constraints. Which group wrote the BEST design problem?
Image/Diagram Description: None
Choices: A) Permanently tape all papers, B) Magnets and metal clips — hold papers but let students lift them, C) Stronger fan, D) Throw away papers
Scenario Justification: Engineering design problem with specific constraints (hold papers + allow lifting). Students evaluate which design meets both constraints.
SEP Justification: Engages 'Engaging in Argument from Evidence' — evaluating designs against specific criteria. Students must check both constraints.
DCI Justification: Requires applying engineering design thinking — solutions must meet ALL constraints.
CCC Justification: Engages Systems (constraints interact) and Structure and Function (magnets + metal clips serve specific function).
Key Recommendation: Excellent engineering design question with dual constraints.

Stem: Desert lizards — light tan and dark brown — released into pale sand area. Data: 13 of 15 light tan survived vs 7 of 15 dark brown. Which explanation is best supported?
Image/Diagram Description: Data table showing survival rates of two lizard color morphs in pale sand environment.
Choices: A) Light tan advantage — blended with pale sand so hawks couldn't see them, B) Dark brown advantage — darker skin makes animals faster, C) Light tan — different species hawks don't eat, D) Dark brown advantage — fewer alive means more space
Scenario Justification: Excellent natural selection scenario with real survival data. Students must analyze data and select the evidence-based explanation. Rich phenomenon.
SEP Justification: Engages 'Analyzing and Interpreting Data' and 'Constructing Explanations from Evidence' — students analyze survival data and evaluate competing explanations.
DCI Justification: Requires applying understanding of adaptation, camouflage, and natural selection to explain differential survival. Deep DCI engagement.
CCC Justification: Engages Cause and Effect (skin color → camouflage → survival) and Patterns (differential survival rates as evidence of selective advantage).
Key Recommendation: Outstanding question. Real data, competing explanations, natural selection reasoning. Approaches Doing Science level.
